Author::::Glostforwords
DateTime::::2016-03-10T11:43:02Z
A city-based franchise system will lead inevitably to the smaller counties going to the wall. There is no way the profits can be equitably shared as the big test match grounds hosting the games will want the lion's share of the profit for doing the work. The smaller counties will also lose out on the current T20 games that make them money especially the local derbies. Having said that there is no guarantee the city-based system will work anything like as well here as in Oz. In Australia most of the population is concentrated in cities. In the UK that is not the case. Vast areas of the cricket-loving countryside will be disenfranchised. There is a solution, not perfect, but workable - have 6 regional teams each made up of 3 counties each. These could be West: Somerset, Glos, Glam; South: Surrey, Sussex, Hants, South East: Kent, Essex, Middlesex; South Midlands: Worcs, Warwick, Northants; North Midlands: Leics, Derbys, Notts; North: Yorks, Lancs, Durham. You can call the teams what you like, but the principle would be that all the sides get games played on the county home grounds. I know some grounds are smaller so profits might be less and some apportioning of profits might be possible to offset that, and I know there will be some resistance to Yorks/Lancs for example being bedfellows, but at least this system would give a vested interest to all the counties and engage non-city based cricket lovers. Play this in a four week period July/August so you can still have some championship matches early July, late August. Finally keep the appointment to view county version of the NatWest Blast for Friday nights throughout the season - this was working reasonably well. One casualty of this might have to be the 50 over competition as Mr Selvey suggests, but I have a feeling that that format of the game is steadily dying - witness the declining crowds at the finals recently.



